properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system currently over Manitoba is spreading rain through central Manitoba. Cold air will sweep into the area as this low tracks towards Ontario tonight, transitioning the rain to wet snow. The snow will continue through Saturday, leaving accumulations of 10 to 20 cm in its wake. While snow is expected throughout the Thompson region, the heavy snow will occur south of the city of Thompson. The rain will transition to snow near midnight in Norway house, and overnight in Island Lake. The snow will begin to taper off Saturday afternoon in Thompson and Saturday evening in Norway House and Island Lake. Along with the snow, there is potential for freezing rain to develop with this system, notably over the Norway House and Island Lake regions. The potential for freezing rain for these communities exists overnight and into Saturday early morning. Please refer to the public forecasts for more details. And stay alert for updated warnings. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A low pressure system currently over northwestern Ontario is bringing heavy snow to central Manitoba today. The heaviest snowfall will occur in a broad swath between Cross lake through Oxford House, Gods Lake and Red Sucker Lake. Snowfall totals of 10 to 25 cm are expected including the amount that fell Friday night. This is heavy, wet snow that could potentially cause damage to trees and power lines. The snow will gradually weaken through the afternoon and end this evening as the weather system continues to push away from the area. Please refer to the public forecasts for more details. And stay alert for updated warnings. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Spring storm on tap for Alberta… A complex weather system currently developing off the BC coast will bring a sharp change in the weather for Alberta later this weekend. Widespread and potentially heavy precipitation will be a concern for western and central portions of the province starting Sunday afternoon and continuing into Monday. Precipitation will start off as rain but will likely change to snow overnight in some locales, particularly for those higher elevations west of Edmonton and Red Deer. Strong gusty winds will also be a concern on the back side of this low, mainly in the foothills. A great deal of uncertainty still exists regarding the timing and location of the rain and snow, including the anticipated amounts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant amounts of snow and freezing rain expected. A low pressure system approaching the area will bring a mix of rain, snow and freezing rain. Precipitation will transition to snow or freezing rain this morning as temperatures fall to near or slightly below the freezing mark. Freezing rain may persist for several hours before completely changing over to snow later this morning. Snow will continue into Saturday night before tapering off Sunday morning. Total snowfall amounts of 15 cm are possible. In addition, strong northeasterly winds of 40 gusting to 60 km/h, combined with snow, may result in blowing snow and reduced visibility. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong wind gusts late this afternoon. A strong cold front will sweep across the south coast this afternoon, accompany with strong gusty winds. Over Greater Victoria and the lower mainland, winds will rise to southeast 30 to 60 km/h late this morning or early this afternoon then shift to southwesterly 40 to 60 km/h gusting up to 80 late this afternoon as the front passes. Winds will ease early this evening. Over Howe Sound, strong northerly outflow of 40 to 60 km/h will shift to southerly inflow 40 to 60 km/h gusting to 80 late this afternoon then ease to light early this evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Flurries are expected over high elevation highway routes of the southern BC interior tonight. A vigorous cold front will cross the southern interior of BC tonight. Rain will begin this evening, but as cold air moves in behind the front snow levels will drop rapidly. As this happens rain will change to flurries over higher elevations. 5 to 10 cm of snow is possible over higher elevations of the Coquihalla Highway - Hope to Merritt. The Okanagan Connector - Pennask Summit, Highway 3 - Allison Pass, and Highway 3 - Paulson Summit to Kootenay Pass will likely see 2 to 5 cm. Strong, gusty winds are also possible with the passage of the front. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Shoreline Ice Pile Up Potential On The South Shore Of Lake Winnipeg, Lake Manitoba And Lake Winnipegosis
properties.Summary:
Description: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. The Hydrologic Forecast Centre of Manitoba Infrastructure is warning there is a moderate to high risk of shoreline ice pile up for today from 1PM to midnight on the south shore of Lake Winnipeg, Lake Manitoba and Lake Winnipegosis due to strong northwest winds. Property owners in the affected area should take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong wind gusts early this evening. A cold front approaching the BC coast will sweep across the southern interior early this evening. Brief but strong, gusty winds, as well as isolated thunderstorms, are to be expected. For the Fraser Canyon, southerly winds of 60 km/h gusting to 80 are forecast this evening. The southern Okanagan Valley, including Penticton, can expect very strong westerly wind gusts reaching 80 km/h early in the evening. The potential for heavy but brief downpours and isolated thunderstorms also exists. Areas from Similkameen to South Thompson, and eastwards to the northern Okanagan Valley and the Shuswap, strong southwesterly wind gusts of 60 to 70 km/h are expected early in the evening. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
